\paragraph{Context}
The theorem concerns strong stability of polynomials, defined in the context of stability regions for linear multistep methods. A polynomial is strongly stable if all its zeros lie inside the open unit disc.

Let $P$ be a polynomial of degree $n$; its type is a triple $(n_{1}, n_{2}, n_{3})$ where $n_{1}$ is the number of zeros in the open unit disc, $n_{2}$ on the unit circle, $n_{3}$ outside the closed unit disc. A polynomial is \emph{strongly stable} if it has type $(n, 0, 0)$, meaning all zeros are in the open unit disc.
